Parliament has not ratified the amendment for Tymosenko's release
The Ukrainian parliament has refused, as part of an amendment to the criminal law, the proposed annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
At second reading, MEPs rejected the draft amendment aimed at reducing the penalties for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years' imprisonment for having entered into a pre-eminent disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must decide on the appeal of the convicted person in December.
Tymosenko described the ruling as political vengeance of the regime and caused a process of suspicion of court bias also in the west.
The draft annulment of paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Premère Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
