Eating an obese child: don't eat breakfast and take cold meats for dinner
More than one third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% are above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with an unhealthy lifestyle.
This shows once again how important the environment in which human beings evolve and the models that surround them are.
On tables of obese children, for example, we find cold meats 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had french fries at dinner according to the survey carried out with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In families of big kids sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most of today's schoolchildren - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place in the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is no coincidence," supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever Company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students in the sixth to third grades have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors causing a dramatic increase in the number of overweight and even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned say, for example, eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch-tasting-dinner, which is a basic principle of good nutrition," says one of the survey results.
Without breakfast and cold meats at dinner
Specialists point out that healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of the pupils' families eat at the same time.
In the majority of families everyone has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that has been noted is that one tenth of the population does not have breakfast at all.
Breakfast is, however, the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that in the families of obese children unhealthy fries are used more often.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sport regularly, but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Get your food ready.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet from the possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating."
Among their favourite dishes are a lot of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is a great preference for sweet lemonades," is indicated in the results of the survey.
For lunch it was the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
Children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Health focus
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a survey of a group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the awareness session" Obesity is no coincidence, "there was a strong commitment to a healthy diet," the survey results indicate.
For example, the most striking was in the case of sweet lemonades, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread flour or potato pellets).
