History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago and originally had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was named IBM in 1924 - originally a trademark used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four companies whose history is linked to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers," the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 presided over the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the company's founder - Watson's ideas have been the foundation of society's identity and culture to date.
Watson was the head of the Kusk firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name says, began with the production of all possible machinery for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During the first four years of Watson's leadership, sales increased to $9 million and began to expand in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that, after 40 years of management, his son occupied the chair of director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s the people and computers of IBM helped NASA to guide flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first computer family - the IBM System / 360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but purchased Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
IBM's successful strategy over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet."
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas that have not yet been exploited, such as transport and urban management.
As far as the IBM trade sector is concerned, a "Smarter Commerce" platform has recently been developed which helps traders manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history also on our territory.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also Brno's strategic outsourcing centre.
The Central Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team which is responsible for the recognition of speech.
