How travel prices have changed since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
The travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, because travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists travelled for holidays in East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination to the west and the trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
The travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, however, it was necessary to line up all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it wasn't won yet.
The currency agreement that was the condition for travelling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the foreign exchange agreement (western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were therefore many country houses and cottages that the Czechs were buying and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, the journeys of the Czechs have experienced a great revolution.
Although up to 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4 million holiday days abroad in countries all over the world.
The great paradox that we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s of the last century in the neighbouring countries of the west caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in the parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a Czech trip at that time was to take with oneself his own canned food, sausage, etc... to save money.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech koruna, which finally allowed our tourists after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased, which has caused another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to growing demand for travel, travel agencies have begun to prepare tours with air charter connections since 1997, which through contracts have dramatically reduced costs compared to what was before.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world, apart from the EU, which later facilitated our travel.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when was prepared the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50, 3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including ancillary expenses.
