Peter Englund's new book, entitled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War," begins with a long list of characters that shake your heart.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page and make it your own page mark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic story by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during these few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the haze of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which issues the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He has written here an extraordinary book which he accurately describes as "an anti-history book."
It has some known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and materials.
It is not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." It contains "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from the two sides of the war, from schoolgirls and botanists to escalators, doctors, paramedics and vendors.
Some of them will become heroes.
Others of the prisoners of war, some of whom will lose limbs, go mad or lose their lives.
Their lives fluctuate here like the candles of a church: while some are dying, new ones are being re-ignited.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
He refuted the idea that the First World War was only a terrible trench war on the western front.
"Beauty and grief" skilfully describes other war theatres: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one spend Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people such as a natural disaster, such as a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When gunshots ring in the distance, and you're a housewife, are you staying or running away?
Who's coming anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been compounded by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumors."
"Beauty and grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor of the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are best preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most address deprivation and the ability to cope.
By telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, false aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He continues on alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a false wood bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 licensed surrogate meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 surrogate coffees."
There are stories about honor and courage.
An American acknowledges his own drive towards savagery and says about the war: "You feel that after all, this is what men were meant to be for, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a varnish is synonymous with civilization, and that there is no barbarian behind your stuffed and nailed shirt.
