After this summer's tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how do we find them?
Easy... log on to Facebook.
"We realized it wasn't so hard to find them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a report recently published by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific precision - the way mercaticians have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of extreme right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of connecting them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
By contacting these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 extreme right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"This is a new way of doing research," says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen."
DEMOS 'study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new and indispensable tool in the hands of scientists.
Focus groups, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through "I Like," publications on walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the "data supernova" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn't approach on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You were supposed to surrender to the party, but they would never have allowed you to enter," says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others said that the site could provide a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their feats in a state of intoxication were considerably more likely to be alcoholic than discreet students.
Megan Moreno suggested that students' colleagues, such as counsellors, could monitor the site and possibly intervene to help a student whose status would too often talk about alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you don't diagnose it," says Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Centre for Child Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses information from its users.
The data team at the site studied statistics on the love situation and Valentine's Day, the turnout in the 2010 mid-term elections and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available - the champions of digital freedom have long argued that the site could make its data treasure available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometres away, the site is allowed access to your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined instructions on how to collect information other than via the Internet, it is something else on-line.
"I don't think many users have ever thought about a researcher being able to study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, based on a 2006 study he conducted by observing his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they know, exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things," says Selwyn.
This is why, despite his experience as a technological researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notepad and pen remain the best tools that can be used.
