How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines shows how widespread deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Penn State administrators were charged with perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman Anthony Weiner, who is famous for the Internet, has turned out to be an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with violations of campaign funding related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of the people who lived history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton started by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating at the school and university tests are legion.
There have been instances in which teachers gave test responses to students in order to gain insight into their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How many deception do we meet?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or detecting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout: "I got you," the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, particularly in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't stutter, blush, or shake.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and still emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating, or managing.
Good liars are able to read others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "focused on them" while women say more lies "focused on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, the others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is called "establishing benchmarks."
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring future changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the vocal quality.
You need to know if someone is normally stirring their feet permanently so that you don't make unfair accusations when you see them stirring their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal deceptive behaviour.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
The deceitful people can immobilize the top of their body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet towards the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interviewers often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to your subject's vocabulary.
The famous Scott Peterson skirted using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
The deceptive individuals can also use a distant language: "I did not have sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wood tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the answer perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
