In the first year of Mario López Valdez's management, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has decreased and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled of change, that generated high expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing billions of losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historical decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the frost allocation report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there were 582 million 835 hectares of crop damage, of which a 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main affected crops were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a constant increase in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment of the State during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated increase, since while from January to March 55,053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the Active Economic Population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to increase to 6.19 per cent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18,969 persons.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because it is not easy for people who earn dollars illegally to work to earn them, invest them and use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the increase in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been limited, first because of the difficulties of entry and second because they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which means that unemployment is rising," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market worsens by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, the 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for lag for the state are low wages, the entity has lower remuneration of the Country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecasting.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was 5,352 pesos, well below the national average of 7,375 pesos, until September.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 the largest reduction in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years was recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June, the FDI of the State reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State records a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by the companies of the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the scenario of economic contraction, the Government of the State applied to the public congress in July for approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municiens, with the objective of reactivating the economy, the approval of the congress of the State was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no profit of indebtedness was observed in any sector of the economy of the State.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government shows a lack of management capacity in the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wishes of the various sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align the effort of all and above all the already synchronized good progress of this new government team, hopefully next year is much better," he said.
Economic Lender
Loredo López stated that events such as the frosts of the beginning of the year held back the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flux is produced by several events, between which frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, President of the Patronale Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that the state is to be channelled towards more dynamic productive activities.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa be exhausted," he says.
Much to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channeled the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to deliver good results in various areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term programme," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that much has been done and the Government is aware that there is still much to do," he says.
Convicted for 8 kilos of marihuana
One resident in Novolato was sentenced to five years in prison and a fine of 100 days for possession of eight kilos of marihuana.
