Debts to contributions to works
Works of a social nature contemplated in programmes such as Hábitat, Rescate de Espacios Públicos and 3x1 para migrantes may not be finished or record serious delays due to lack of economic resources, said Miguel Ángel López Miranda.
The Director of Municipal Social Development indicated that, although so far construction programmes have progressed, they are at risk, as the Government of the State has not fulfilled its obligations to offer contributions in excess of 11 million pesos in all three programmes.
He pointed out that the total investment of these three programs is approximately 50 million pesos, of which the state must provide 25 percent and so far only the Federation and the Municipal have provided resources for the works, therefore there is the possibility of a delay in their finalization.
"They have to make a contribution of 12 million and despite the fact that the year will soon end they have given us nothing, even if since July they had to give us a part," he says, "and we, in order not to record delays, have started the works and we have made much progress, but we need the money."
He mentioned that last year, during the administration of Jesús Aguilar Padilla, the State had not paid the corresponding contributions, therefore at the beginning of the administration the Municipal had to apply for a credit to cover the 7 million that the State administration had not provided at that time.
"We had experienced this in the previous six-year period because the state had not had the economic capacity to participate and the programs continue to work, and this year, in order to have access to these programs, we had to get the resources to cover what the state had not paid," he explained.
Despite the fact that there is a commitment on the part of the State authorities to provide these resources, he stated that they had made a request to the Secretary of Administration and Finance, Armando Villarreal, to activate the management so that the corresponding percentages would arrive as soon as possible.
"They have to supply almost 12 million and despite the fact that the year will soon end, they have not given us anything."
The Court validates "the analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analogue signals by digital is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been combined.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was rejected for failing to reach a qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as non-constitutional, because radio and television regulation is an assignment reserved by law to the Federal Commission on Telecommunications (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reserve of law.
In favour of the project only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero even voted.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and admit the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions planned by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of the Ministers also resolved to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the minister president said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures for the public administration to prepare for it.
"I also consider that if it were to do so, the autonomy of the regulatory body would be affected," and he recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, which has the constitutional mandate of State leadership.
The substitution of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has suffered in recent years and is reflected in better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Adjournment of the change, he argued, would postpone the benefits of digitalisation, which involves a decision in the public interest that has not only a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These questions, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of the economic direction of the State, includes a group of powers that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State."
He recalled that a large number of countries all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done so through the Executive, despite the fact that they have very specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, has somehow invaded the sphere of competence of Congress, as it ensures in the administrative sphere compliance with the laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
The possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán is analysed.
According to the data provided by PREP, the difference between the first and second places in the Governor's election is only 27 per cent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,774 total minutes.
The possibility of the "vote by vote" count is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Preliminary Electoral Results Programme (PREP) the difference between the first and second places of the governor's election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6,774 total minutes.
In this connection, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, in the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local standards with federal electoral reform.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not certify either his Political Constitution or his State Electoral Code or his Electoral Justice Act, at the same time as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline for this electoral trial to enter into force, and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted his publication within the time limits prescribed by the Law of the State Official Gazette, with the argument that he had some objections.
On 9 November, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local legislature and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the State agent for constitutional reforms, as it has no right to "sanction or challenge them."
Interviewed on the possibility of "voting by vote," María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of votes by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, of one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes coincide; there are no minutes of voting and there are no counts in the ballot box record at the President's office; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the votes received in all ballot boxes in the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to win the respective election and the candidate who obtained the second place in the election is equal to or below one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the party representative and / or coalition that presented the second of the candidates reported.
The total count may also be carried out if, at the end of the common count, the difference between the alleged winner and the second-place candidate is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is an express petition from the representative of the political party from which the candidate has been placed second, in which case the electoral packages which have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the Morelia election, where according to the PREP, the difference between first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
