The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the verge of economic disaster
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the verge of economic disaster and put the whole Eurozone in jeopardy.
A communiqué from the presidential palace announced that Monti, named Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the Government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed of technocrats in his majorities, although it is not clear when the new executive takes up his post.
Monti said he was going to present to the president the results of his talks with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "framework is now well-framed," he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy is fighting a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels that are impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Highlighting the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of the Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employers Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would very much support this government."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, to which the crisis forced him to resign on last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," said Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, to the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed Monti's technocratic majority government.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any deadlock or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign benches added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers & apos; groups and youth and women & apos; s organizations.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday at night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who allowed an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of €1.9 trillion, would be too much for Eurozone's current financial defences.
Monti said that his Government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give him time to implement the reforms before moving the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual distrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
