Quinteto has included the country in its turn to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become reality"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bass player Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts on the National Stadium on Sunday.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream become reality to happen in this country.
It is that bass player and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva of Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of its tour celebrating two decades of work and Sunday 20 will make its only stop in Central America.
That day will be on the National Stadium, starting at 7: 30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles Group The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the complete transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream that has come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been grandiose.
I spent in Costa Rica only once the holidays; it is such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So it makes us very emotional to wear our music there.
I ask you, because there is some kind of devotion to the band, fans live intensely on previous days.
What is your message to your fervent followers?
Thank you for staying next to us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to arrive in Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass to this concert.
A few people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a little pressure to your visit.
Some of the larger shows we have offered over the past 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We have offered a two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to it.
We love this country, we love surfing and jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of friends surfing and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are incredible there.
My friends were always surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned, through the surfists who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you offered huge shows, with lots of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to do the best possible show, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the directory.
What's this all about?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, which is why it's very difficult to choose which songs to perform each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played for a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you're celebrating 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us had imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together makes us very emotional.
We love each other and love to create music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of major groups.
We're very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
This is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much more strange when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw in Soundgarden in their tour, so we're lucky to be friends again with all of them and it's an honor for us to form part of this Seattle sound that came up.
It's also very strange that a group like yours is holding together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us were together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
First, I believe that we are all lucky to be still alive, and second, we are all concerned about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and that could not be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
