Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official procession, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica and made up of various ministers and bosses, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with its Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of a long agenda of meetings with political and trade authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayan residents in Mexico, according to the agenda circulated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two Presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be "conducive to the exchange of information in political affairs between the two nations," according to the information published by the South American Presidency on its web page.
According to local media, Mujica is trying to convince Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that took place when the French agent, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country on the list of tax havens, in the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that led to the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations by its ambassador from this European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world's strongest emerging and developed countries, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year, a convention to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of the tax exchange agreements to get out of the "gri list" of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), integrated by countries that do not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
On the trade front, Mexico and Uruguay have in force since 2004 a Free Trade Treaty (TLC) which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
