"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so the unit met the requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that investigations in the impacting area did not report the appearance of ground parts.
"In one research it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was structurally present.
"The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to transport them.
The soil had a pant of seven to 30 degrees inclination.
For the time being, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as quickly as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto López Meyer, General Manager of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that the moment of impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Major State was operating at cruising speed and this took place on a soft, ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruising at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, the SCT holder, Pérez Jácome, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the Aeronautical Standards, the flight was conducted according to visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
The reports in the AICM indicated adequate take-off conditions, and as the aircraft advanced to the boundary area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low cloud layers.
Selected roads:
It is likely that due to the cloud conditions, the crew sought an area of lower height and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft remains in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact has taken place on a straight and lateral path.
The aircraft remains dispersal model suggests that the helicopter struck the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
Traces of fire or explosion were not detected:
In the location of the disaster there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,2200 feet above the middle sea level, and the ground had a slope that had since seven drifts to 30 degrees inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides evidence that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After a thorough search in an area larger than the surrounding area around the accident, dispersive parts of the aircraft were not found, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Social Insurance Institute (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene for children and young people, known as the 'Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents' protocol, which will allow for markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Investigation Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialties of the 20th Century National Medical Centre, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Investigation and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation involves the participation of the population entitled or not, and the participation of the IMSS sports units in Valle de México, where evidence is provided to minors every Saturday from 8: 00 am.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtemoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Sportive Independencia Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Sportive Morelos Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that of knowing the components and importance of genetics in the development of obesity and identifying risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the development of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the aim is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of the specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturdays, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin, and genetic (looking to identify people associated with childhood obesity) will be applied to all participants.
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in only six years there was an increase of 77 per cent in obesity for boys and 47 per cent for girls; overweight was also seen a dramatic increase," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others in its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 per cent Indo-American inheritance, a 30 per cent European and a five per cent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that, in general, the genetics of obesity results in the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the full assessment of children, which allows for the detection of overweight or obesity.
It also says that the presence of dark-coloured folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicates the likelihood of suffering metabolic and even pre-diabetic alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, with physicians giving it to parents in writing, explaining each of the measures and lifestyle changes that they need to make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentarism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high calorie intake, that is, the greater consumption of sweet drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat pâté with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves - bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analysed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrant
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signs that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand currants each rainy season in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavement is adequate, the currants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference Une opinion technologique sur les cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera considered that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and therefore the formation of blackcurrant.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malagasy, which together give the pavement its viscoelastic behaviour characteristic.
The viscoelastic behaviour of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, nearly 180 degrees, behave like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes breaking, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Ciudad de México were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involved asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and compacted later.
Each of the small stones forming the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it by generating effort, this allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, it would spread better, but it was thought to be a chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one puts a final layer called a bearing layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide grip in the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the bearing layer also requires that it be of adequate thickness and that the material it is made of be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because these affect considerably the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes currants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that is ruined is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not happen immediately, but it is a process that must be cured at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, in order to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow to repair blackcurrant easily and without having to use high temperatures.
