So was the work of the person of Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano
A typist from Cali has gone to history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano."
The work of these officials is crucial.
The past 4 November a typist of the CTI of Cali passed to history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the Farc: "Alfonso Cano," comparing his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working in the field of judicial investigation for 21 years.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the dead bodies were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after having completed appropriate courses, he specialized in typing, which is the study of friction skin, that is, palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliazar was warned to take with him clothes for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that it was suspected that one of them was the man who ruled the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to carry the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, as it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant in the area, without glasses and much more lean.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a collector and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the Farc.
Searching for the print
For a typist from Sijín de Cali, the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano," is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our job.
Typing is an exact science, with no margin of error, which can be crucial in the resolution of crimes.
Apart from identifying corpses, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of captured persons.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have documents.
We take their fingerprints and search the database for them.
The researcher told that in a case of theft he had to remove part of a wall from a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate areas to draw a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint from all hands and identify the offender who had participated in various robberies," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Interference from the investigation it was determined that a parent could be suspected of the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him at the scene of the crime.
An ITC typist explained that "fingerprints of objects with chemical or physical reagents are extracted."
When they appear, a sampler or tape is used to collect them.
Later, the prints are sent to Asif, the database of the decliners, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He explained that not everything is shown in the CSI television program.
Like everything that shines is not gold, everything you touch doesn't necessarily become a fingerprint.
It can, however, be used if the necessary confrontation is achieved.
The "indignant" defy authorities in New York City
Hundreds of protesters rushed in front of Zuccotti Square to camp there.
A large proportion of the people reached the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
The integrants of the Occupupe Wall Street movement challenged the New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, through a judicial order, Manhattan instead, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another Great Apple park.
Hundreds of protesters were rushing in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access through a judicial order that allowed the 'indignants' to camp again in that place, while the other side of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new arrests.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp again in the square, we will settle in another place and we will continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful demonstrations," says one of the spokesmen of the "Occupy Wall Street" movement, Mark Bray.
Bray detailed that the response of the 'indignants' to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg came to the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order prohibiting the forced evacuation of the area and allowing the demonstrators to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignants' occupied a new park at the confluence of Canal Street and Sixth Avenue, very close to the entrance to Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church Parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but after the police moved there and arrested some demonstrators, although Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are centenarians of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders moved in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene on their behalf in front of the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a private building - remains closed pending the celebration of a judicial hearing scheduled for Tuesday, during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analysed.
Some protesters previously displaced were carrying and distributing copies of this court order at that time and they were even handing it over to the agents who were watching the square, which caused 'some small clashes', said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials hit the demonstrators.
The judicial order prohibits the authorities from evacuating members of Occupupe Wall Street or applying 'laws published after the beginning of the occupation or prohibiting demonstrators from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they previously used'.
Mayor Bloomberg told the press that, because of this judicial order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and demonstrators, but warned them that local laws did not allow them to settle with tents and sleeping bags.
The municipal councilman personally defended the evacuation at dawn in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and decided because the demonstrators were 'breaking the law'.
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the square because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases to hurt others," because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life."
"This morning's evacuation at dawn was repugnant and shows that Bloomberg is more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman for the movement, who accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression."
The officials of "Occupe Wall Street" also indicated that they do not think they will organize "big actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and trade unions to commemorate the two months of protests, which began on September 17.
