Japan Reborn After Earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% due to domestic consumption and puts an end to the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralysed, convalescent even after the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in Japan since the Second World War.
The initial estimates of the Tokyo Government had calculated property losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seemed to have diminished.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, data from the Gross Domestic Product between July and September were used to turn the page permanently: GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualised rates.
The second quarter - for Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the highest rate of increase since January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of the acquisition of equipment to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, firms increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% decrease in capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly as a result of changes in domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "safe havens" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the Eurozone and the trouble forecast of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic floating line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, had the yen's contribution responsible for their poor performance between July and September.
While markets continue to hold their seats in the peripheral EU countries, the Government of Yoshihiko Noda does not lower the guard.
"We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said the Secretary of State for Economic Policy, Motohisa Furukawa.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being curtailed.
For it dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in level 100, n lowering eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
