A measure that could provoke anger, but which would bring in 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic in scope: to impose on civil servants a day of non-compensable default in the event of a stoppage of work (so far they have no waiting period, compared with three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also relaunches the issue of fraud, this time targeting abuses linked to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, if you are caught, you will pay back," said Xavier Bertrand at the RTL microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the advertising effects appear to be somewhat disproportionate to the reality of fraud at work stoppages.
Since 2002, it has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us start by looking at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, at €11.3 billion.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, i.e. EUR 6.2 billion.
And so 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days of work stoppage, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
An average that conceals clear discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management website Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any sick days off.
Another study, this time from the Health Insurance, states that in 2010, 37% of sick stoppages were of less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more prone than elsewhere to work stoppages.
A long study carried out in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001 the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) in France ranged from 10% to 11%, compared with 20% to 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sick-stop fraud represents very little in the face of undeclared work.
Fraud is only a small problem.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 has meant that checks are systematic on sick stoppages of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 carried out for short-term stoppages were "unjustified or too long," i.e. 37,050 cases.
For stoppages of more than 45 days, which were systematically monitored, 11% of the 1.2 million, or 132,000, cases were "inadequate or unjustified."
In total, therefore, 169 000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who have had a sick leave.
A figure which represents very little face to face, for example, with that of black work.
According to MP UMP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would represent EUR 9-15 billion in tax losses per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud.
