It is necessary to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
In the area of palliative care, the Committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer cases.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions under which they want to die and make arrangements.
This was one of the findings of a major Royal Society of Canada report, which involved six experts in a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
The Committee recommends that the Government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, to be made available to a patient who is deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them eventually die in hospital.
Overall, this rate is highest in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that contradict the position of the federal government, which has already stated that it does not want to change the Criminal Code with respect to euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in the application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on unskilled or unconsenting persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, said yesterday in a teleconference, there would be more cases of such overflows precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favor of euthanasia
It should be recalled that 85% of Canadians have already spoken out in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would help end-of-life people alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid survey conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are less valuable.
As for those who had committed assisted suicide, 41 per cent felt that they should not be prosecuted.
The situation regarding the maintenance or cessation of care with a patient is less clear, the authors of the report say.
