The government of the leading social-democratic / Christian-democratic coalition in Austria decided on Tuesday to include in the constitution a "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid any deterioration by the rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann himself who announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt was 74.6%, well above the 60% ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
