Energy policy:
the facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is a subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and competitiveness of businesses.
It is healthy for an election to be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear power has in them.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
With 7 billion people on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources will have to be addressed in order to continue to produce electricity at all times, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the environmental debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to be able to find an alternative source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which is just planning to build only last generation power plants.
On the other hand, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, continue their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to their park by resuming the construction of a power plant that was interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
While the German model, which focuses on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality makes discourse difficult.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, a rise in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal-fired power stations.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be pondered.
Europe's wind power champion, from which he draws 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to intermittent wind; by this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to our constant energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial tool on national territory, French companies benefit from Europe 's cheapest electricity.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear energy would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make the beautiful declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power illusory.
A price which a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show any opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
It should be recalled that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125 000 direct jobs and 410 000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it brings a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very job-creating non-relocatable.
If France were to decide to break out of nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the annual 6 billion euros of French nuclear equipment and services exports.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miracle source of electricity production, nor is there any diabolical source of electricity.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions is evidence of the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We have in France a Safety Authority which exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville yard.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession of safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the safety authorities, French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a concept that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians willing to build a power plant, the shutdown of its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift to the competitors of Areva and EDF by giving them the free way to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers dominate such a crucial debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the statistics policy, compatibility of this policy with France's self-proclaimed status as a "country of human rights."
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that was the subject of the news, with the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of 23 May) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant servers."
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers," and on the left by Michel Rocard, who explained that France "cannot accept all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on the left as well as on the right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be accorded to immigrants.
In his program, François Hollande confines himself to triviality, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem."
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay for it electively, but it is very expensive economically.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and harms employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that migrants may replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, who exert downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly engaged in occupations in sectors where there is a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not keep up with the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
Just as it will be difficult for a surgeon to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrival of immigrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows results in an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages over the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (a high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
For example, the World Labour Organisation estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue less expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average over his or her entire life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for missing growth points "with his teeth."
The teeth in question, by being used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, remains to think European democracy
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him, who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the 20th century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have thought that it would be enough, for democracy to triumph over its enemies once and for all, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way.
Since Napoleon "Le Petit," we know that this was an easy thought.
Universal suffrage, in order to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not enough and can even be made "an instrument of oppression," as the Republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also, first and foremost, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinodia of the true-false Greek referendum has had the value of double revealing in this respect: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them Republican soldiers are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in scattered order.
A white-seing to the European absolute monarch or a paired foot jump in the void of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cutlets, but we want a common exercise, of right, serene and continuous, of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal - there is no place to stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that is bent on the dictates of markets and credit rating agencies, which suffers from its powerlessness and lack of solidarity.
It is Europe as a whole that is humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgent need is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
It is together that Europeans will be able to reduce their debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The end of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except, of course, to lead us to disaster.
After a long time of fighting this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for the European Economic Government.
All right.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The revolution in interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe politically, a true European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
