The North Stream, the new Russian gas gateway in Europe
The North Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe and Russia to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered into operation.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event brilliantly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly with Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic metres of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe via an initial 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, delivering a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction project has the air of victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will indeed allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any ground passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries are losing some of their power: it is becoming more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare North Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact," referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That means whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in overcoming its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming and whose deposits are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by Gazprom's leaders, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-sheathed steel to protect it from ships' anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
"A hundred people had to be kidnapped or destroyed as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to step up measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts throughout its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project did not do so while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company set up permanently off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds for a leak every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is monitored by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one metre in diameter, and it is pushed by gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, he provides accurate information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It's 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to the company, for 20 years renewable, the entire gas transport capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their costs, since only Gazprom assumes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskin, a notebook.
Created about 15 years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskin wants to give back the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskin notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, elastic, broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskin notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook of notes.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is based on an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnish cotton used to cover banquettes, for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travellers.
"Moleskin has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is here.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to the previous 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first few years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskin crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw up a sketch of the buyer, as the notebook seduces the businessman as well as the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskin, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The Italian small business, which had 12 employees at its beginning, now has almost 100 employees and has two offices since 2008, one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We have followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the growth of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskin: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, calendar, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a wide range of media.
An envious success: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskin.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a pro-active public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the general population.
Discouraging?
"No," says Eric Blanchet, Managing Director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
"The progress made over the past 15 years has been considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before they can enter employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualifications: 80% do not have a bachelor's degree and out of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53 per cent for the disabled, compared with 38 per cent on average.
In short, all these criteria make it particularly difficult to return to work and "constitute the crux of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Treplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for objective brakes.
The unsaid, the attitudes that are changing, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability," with an "overrepresentation of persons in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual disabilities."
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers set out in a law of... 1987.
The latest known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Managing Director of Agefiph, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
